Week 2: Rstudio Exercise 2 - Regression and model validation

To develop the linear regression model we use the data, learn2014, is created using the R script in the Data wrangling exercise from the original data learning2014 available at http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt.

The dataframe learn2014 has 166 observations and 7 variables.

In the first figure below, the graphical overview of the data variables, their distributions and relationships are given. The colours in the plot is based on gender. The correlation between variables shows that the variable “attitude” is highly correlated to “points”. The next two variables correlated to “points” are “stra” and “surf” considering the absolute value of the correlation.

So we develop a linear regression model, my_model3, with three variables with the formula “points ~ attitude + stra + surf”. The summary of the my_model3 gives the coefficients of the variables and the Residual standard error as 5.296. The p-value is 3.156e-08.

Next we model my_model2 with two variables attitude and stra. The summary of the my_model3 gives the coefficients of the variables and the Residual standard error as 5.289. The p-value is 7.734e-09.

As the residual error is smaller for my_model 2 and it has a p-value smaller than that of my_model3, we choose my_model2.

The plots show the Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage. These plots provide adequate justification for the assumptions taken for the regression model. The Residuals vs Fitted values are well clustered to suggest that the errors do not grow with the size of the data.

The normal QQ plot is linear suggesting that the normality assumption about the errors are justified. The residual vs leverage plot shows that the outliers do not impact the model.

Logistic regression

In this chapter we analyse the datasets on student alcohol consumption in secondary schools in Portugal using Logistic regression.

The data is obtained from two questionnaires related to student alcohol consumption and is available at UCI Machine Learning Repository, Student Alcohol consumption data page. The data consists of answers to two questionaires, one from math class and another from protugese language class related to student alcohol consumption in secondary school students in Portugal

The purpose of our analysis is to study the relationships between high/low alcohol consumption and some of the influencing variables in the data.

The alc dataset

Using the program create_alc.R we joined the above two datsets to a new datset alc. The alc data set has two new columns alc_use, which is the average of weekday and weekend alcohol consumption and another column high_use which is true if alc_use > 2. This dataset is also available here

The variables (attributes) of alc dataframe

  1. school - student’s school (binary: ‘GP’ - Gabriel Pereira or ‘MS’ - Mousinho da Silveira)
  2. sex - student’s sex (binary: ‘F’ - female or ‘M’ - male)
  3. age - student’s age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
  4. address - student’s home address type (binary: ‘U’ - urban or ‘R’ - rural)
  5. famsize - family size (binary: ‘LE3’ - less or equal to 3 or ‘GT3’ - greater than 3)
  6. Pstatus - parent’s cohabitation status (binary: ‘T’ - living together or ‘A’ - apart)
  7. Medu - mother’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)
  8. Fedu - father’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)
  9. Mjob - mother’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)
  10. Fjob - father’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)
  11. reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to ‘home’, school ‘reputation’, ‘course’ preference or ‘other’)
  12. guardian - student’s guardian (nominal: ‘mother’, ‘father’ or ‘other’)
  13. traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
  14. studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
  15. failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
  16. schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)
  17. famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)
  18. paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)
  19. activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
  20. nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)
  21. higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
  22. internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
  23. romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
  24. famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
  25. freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  26. goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  27. Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  28. Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
  29. health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)
  30. absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)
  31. G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  32. G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  33. G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)
  34. alc_use - average of weekday and weekend alcohol consumption
  35. high_use is True if alc_use > 2

So based on the analysis described here, we have selected the variables sex, absences, failures and the final grade G3 as the explanatory variables for the prediction on high_use ### Answer to question 5 Logistic regression model

m <- glm(high_use ~ absences + sex + failures + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp

# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)

Odds ratio can be used to indicate the extent to which a particular explanatory variable influences high_use.OR value close to one signifies minimal influence whereas the higher the value, the greater is the influence of the variable on the prediction outcome. So we can conclude that the explanatory variable sex has the maximum influece followed by the variables failures, absences and G3 in that order.
(Intercept) absences sexM failures G3 0.2729142 1.0956478 2.5940331 1.4133492 0.9501385

Here we have a categorical variable sex whhich has two levels male and female. To check whether the whole variable Sex improves the model fit, we fit one model with (m1) with variable sex and one without the variable sex (m2) and conduct a likelihood ratio test. This tests the hypothesis that all coefficients of sex are zero:

m1 <- glm(high_use ~ absences + sex + failures + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")
m2 <- glm(high_use ~ absences + failures + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")

anova(m1, m2, test="LRT")
## Analysis of Deviance Table
## 
## Model 1: high_use ~ absences + sex + failures + G3
## Model 2: high_use ~ absences + failures + G3
##   Resid. Df Resid. Dev Df Deviance  Pr(>Chi)    
## 1       377     418.56                          
## 2       378     435.66 -1  -17.105 3.538e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The likelihood ratio test is highly significant and we would conclude that the variable sex should remain in the model.

Answer to question 6

Logistic regression enables to predict binary outcomes. We use the data alc to make the predictions for high:use.

m <- glm(high_use ~ absences + sex + failures + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")
# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)
# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   12
##    TRUE     86   26

We see from the results that the high_use prediction is fairly accurate when the high_use has the state FALSE, and the prediction is rather poor when high_use has the state TRUE.
